Preface

For the final exam/project we will develop classification models using several approaches and compare their performance on a new dataset so-called Census Income from UCI ML. It is available at UCI ML web site, but so that we are not at the mercy of UCI ML availability, there is also a local copy of it in our website in Canvas as a zip-archive of all associated files. Among other things, the description for this dataset also presents performance (prediction accuracy) observed by the dataset providers using variety of modeling techniques this supplies a context for the errors of the models we will develop here.

Please note that the original data has been split up into training and test subsets, but there doesnt seem to be anything particular about that split, so we might want to pool those two datasets together and split them into training and test as necessary ourselves. As you do that, please check that the attribute levels are consistent between those two files. For instance, the categorized income levels are indicated using slightly different notation in their training and test data. By now it should be quite straightforward for you to correct that when you pool them together.

Also, please note that there is non-negligible number of rows with missing values that for most analyses cannot be included without modification in the computation. Please decide how you want to handle them and proceed accordingly. The simplest and perfectly acceptable approach would be to exclude those observations from the rest of the analyses, but if you have time and inclination to investigate the impact of imputing them by various means, you are welcome to try.

Attribute called final weight in the dataset description represents demographic weighting of these observations. Please disregard it for the purposes of this assignment.

Additionally, several attributes in this dataset are categorical variables with more than two levels (e.g.native country, occupation, etc.). Please make sure to translate them into corresponding sets of dummy indicator variables for the methods that require such conversion (e.g.PCA) R function model.matrix can be convenient for this, instead of generating those 0/1 indicators for each level of the factor manually (which is still perfectly fine). Some of those multi-level factors contain very sparsely populated categories e.g.occupation Armed-Forces or work class Never-worked it is your call whether you want to keep those observations in the data or exclude also on the basis that there is not enough data to adequately capture the impact of those categories. Feel free to experiment away!

Among the multi-level categorical attributes, native country attribute has the largest number of levels several folds higher than any other attribute in this dataset some of which have relatively few observations. This associated increase in dimensionality of the data may not be accompanied by a corresponding gain of resolution e.g.would we expect this data to support the difference in income between descendants from Peru and Nicaragua, for example, or from Cambodia and Laos? Please feel free to evaluate the impact of inclusion and/or omission of this attribute in/from the model and/or discretizing it differently (e.g.US/non-US, etc.).

Lastly, the size of this dataset can make some of the modeling techniques run slower than what we were typically encountering in this class. You may find it helpful to do some of the exploration and model tuning on multiple random samples of smaller size as you decide on useful ranges of parameters/modeling choices, and then only perform a final run of fully debugged and working code on the full dataset. Please see also the afterword below on the computational demands of this problem set.



#Loading "adult.data" as dataset of attribte class of characters
#Loading "adult.test" as dataset of attribte class of characters; skiping first row
train.data.tmp = read.table('adult.data', sep = ',', header=F, colClasses = c("character"), strip.white=T)
test.data.tmp = read.table('adult.test', sep = ',', skip=1, header=F, colClasses = c("character"), strip.white=T)

#Correcting income variable in test.data.tmp dataset
test.data.tmp[,15] = ifelse(test.data.tmp[,15] == ">50K.", ">50K", "<=50K")

#rBinding datasets
data = rbind(train.data.tmp,test.data.tmp)

#Setting colnames
colnames(data) = c("age", "workclass", "fnlwgt", "educ", "educNum", "mariStatus", "occupation",
                   "relShip", "race", "sex", "capGain", "capLoss", "hpw", "natCountry", "income")


#Setting all unknown values to NA
#Removing observations that include at least one NA
data[data == "?"] = NA
data = data[complete.cases(data), ]

#Removing observation that have only few observations for categories
data = subset(data, 
                workclass != "Without-pay" &
                occupation != "Armed-Forces")

#nat_country - groupping all observations that are not from US, in non-US
data$natCountry = ifelse(data$natCountry == "United-States", "US", "non-US")

#Categorical/Continuous Variables 
con.att = c("age","educNum","capGain","capLoss","hpw")
cat.att = setdiff(colnames(data),con.att)

#Converting attributes to integer for continiuous and factor categorical variables
for(coln in colnames(data)) {
  if (coln %in% con.att) {
    data[,coln] = as.integer(data[,coln])
  } else {
    data[,coln] = factor(data[,coln])
  }
}

#Decreasing levels of multilevel categorical attributes
levels(data$occupation) = c("Other","Other","ExecMng","Other","Other","Other","Service",
                    "Service","Profi","Service","Other","Service","Other")
levels(data$mariStatus) = c("Divorced","Married","Married","Married","NeverMarried","Separated","Widowed")
levels(data$workclass) = c("Gov","Gov","Private","SEinc","SEnotInc","Gov")


#Setting capGain = capGain-capLoss - to decrease dimensions
data$capGain = data$capGain - data$capLoss

#Excluding "fnlwgt" from dataset
#Excluding "educ" from dataset, since it can be obtained from educ_num
#Excluding "capLoss" from dataset
data = data[,c(-3,-4,-12)]

#Resetting list of categorical/continuous  variables
con.att = c("age","educNum","capGain","hpw")
cat.att = setdiff(colnames(data),con.att)

summPreds <- function(inpPred,inpTruth,inpMetrNms=c("err","acc","sens","spec")) {
  retVals <- numeric()
  for ( metrTmp in inpMetrNms ) {
    retVals[metrTmp] <- performance(prediction(inpPred,inpTruth),measure=metrTmp)@y.values[[1]][2]
  }
  retVals
}

rocplot=function(pred, truth, ...) { 
  predob = prediction(pred, truth) 
  perf = performance(predob, "tpr", "fpr") 
  plot(perf,...)
}

Problem 1: univariate and unsupervised analysis

Download and read Census Income data into R and prepare graphical and numerical summaries of it: e.g.histograms of continuous attributes, contingency tables of categorical variables, scatterplots of continuous attributes with some of the categorical variables indicated by color/symbol shape, etc. Perform principal components analysis of this data (do you need to scale it prior to that? how would you represent multilevel categorical attributes to be used as inputs for PCA?) and plot observations in the space of the first few principal components with subjects gender and/or categorized income indicated by color/shape of the symbol. Perform univariate assessment of associations between outcome we will be modeling and each of the attributes (e.g.t-test or logistic regression for continuous attributes, contingency tables/Fisher exact test/\(\chi^2\) test for categorical attributes). Summarize your observations from these assessments: does it appear that there is association between outcome and predictors? Which predictors seem to be more/less relevant?

PCA

To correctly explain variance of each component we will need to scale attributes. Multilevel categorical attributes in PCA will be represented as additional attribute for each category and intercept using model.matrix.

#PCA
dataTmp = data[order(data$sex, decreasing=T),]
#dataTmp = dataTmp[order(dataTmp$income),]

pca.formula = as.formula(paste0("~0+",paste0( setdiff(colnames(data),c("income")), collapse = "+")))
data.pca = as.data.frame(model.matrix(pca.formula,data=dataTmp))

pca = prcomp(data.pca,scale=T)
summary(pca)

  dfRf = rbind(dfRf,data.frame(type="rfTrain",metric=names(tmpVals),value=tmpVals))
  
}

Problem 4: SVM

Develop SVM model of this data choosing parameters (e.g.choice of kernel, cost, etc.) that appear to yield better performance. Test model performance on multiple splits of data into training and test subsets, summarize model performance in terms of accuracy/error, sensitivity/specificity and compare to the performance of other methods reported in the dataset description.

#Running Linear SVM with default parameters
#svmTrain = svm(income~.,data=data,kernel="linear")
#svmPred = predict(svmTrain,newdata=data)
#tmpVals = summPreds(as.numeric(svmPred),as.numeric(data[,"income"]))
#data.frame(type=paste0("svm","Linear",1),metric=names(tmpVals),value=tmpVals)
#Calculating best parameters using tune function on entire dataset takes too long, for that reason we will get the most frequent parameters in 10 simulations using tune function on random 10% of the data  
#Trying to find better parameters by taking randomly 10% of observation multiple times
tuneParams = NULL
for(i in 1:(nSim/2)) {
  tenProcIdx <- sample(nrow(data),0.1*nrow(data))

  tuneSvm = tune(svm,income~.,data=data[tenProcIdx,],
               ranges=list(kernel=c("linear", "radial", "polynomial"),
                           cost=c(0.1,0.5,1),
                           degree=2:3,
                           gamma=c(0.1,1)))
  
  tuneParams = rbind(tuneParams, data.frame(tuneSvm$best.parameters[1,],
                                            err=tuneSvm$best.performance))
}

tuneParams
##         kernel cost degree gamma       err
## 6   polynomial  0.5      2   0.1 0.1463003
## 8       radial  1.0      2   0.1 0.1644512
## 81      radial  1.0      2   0.1 0.1633435
## 82      radial  1.0      2   0.1 0.1671114
## 21  polynomial  0.1      2   1.0 0.1660146
## 9   polynomial  1.0      2   0.1 0.1600185
## 91  polynomial  1.0      2   0.1 0.1598042
## 83      radial  1.0      2   0.1 0.1615677
## 84      radial  1.0      2   0.1 0.1505043
## 211 polynomial  0.1      2   1.0 0.1573710
#Grouping by params +count/mean.error
mostFreq = aggregate(err~kernel+cost+degree+gamma, data=tuneParams, FUN=function(x) c(ln=length(x),mn=mean(x)))

#First two most frequent params
tuneParamsFreq = mostFreq[order(-mostFreq$err[,"ln"]),][1:min(2,nrow(mostFreq)),]

#Ordering by average error rate
tuneParamsFreq=tuneParamsFreq[order(tuneParamsFreq$err[,"mn"]),]
tuneParamsFreq[1,]
##       kernel cost degree gamma    err.ln    err.mn
## 3 polynomial    1      2   0.1 2.0000000 0.1599114
bestKernel = tuneParamsFreq[1,"kernel"]
bestCost = tuneParamsFreq[1,"cost"]
bestDegree = tuneParamsFreq[1,"degree"]
bestGamma = tuneParamsFreq[1,"gamma"]

dfSvm <- NULL
for ( iSim in 1:nSim ) {
      
      trainIdx <- sample(nrow(data),0.67*nrow(data))

      #SVM 
      svmTrain = svm(income~.,data=data[trainIdx,],
                     kernel=bestKernel,
                     cost=bestCost,
                     degree=bestDegree,
                     gamma=bestGamma)
      svmPred = predict(svmTrain,newdata=data[-trainIdx,])
      tmpVals = summPreds(as.numeric(svmPred),as.numeric(data[-trainIdx,"income"]))
      dfSvm = rbind(dfSvm,data.frame(type="svm",metric=names(tmpVals),value=tmpVals))
}
ggplot(rbind(dfSvm,dfTmp),aes(x=type,y=100*value,colour=type)) + geom_boxplot() + facet_wrap(~metric,ncol=4,scales="free") + xlab("") + ylab("") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

Extra: variable importance in SVM

SVM does not appear to provide readily available tools for judging relative importance of different attributes in the model. Please evaluate here an approach similar to that employed by random forest where importance of any given attribute is measured by the decrease in model performance upon randomization of the values for this attribute.

#vanilladot-linear
#rbfdot-radial
#polydot-polynomial

#sigma-gamma
#c-cost
#d-degree

svmKernel = data.frame(kernel=c("vanilladot","rbfdot","polydot"))
rownames(svmKernel)=c("linear","radial","polynomial")

kparTmp = "automatic"
if(bestKernel=="radial") {
  kparTmp = list(sigma=bestGamma)
} else if(bestKernel=="polynomial") {
  kparTmp = list(d=bestDegree)
}


svmModel = fit(income~., data=data, model="svm", 
               kernel=as.character(svmKernel[bestKernel,"kernel"]),
               C=bestCost,
               kpar=kparTmp
               )
svmImp = Importance(svmModel, data=data, method="1D-SA")

#Relative importance for each attribute
relImp = cbind(colnames(data), round(svmImp$imp,digits=2))
relImp = relImp[order(relImp[,2]),]
